<subsection><title>Perimeter</title>
  <p>When we speak of the perimeter of a region, we usually mean the outer edge or boundary of the region. In mathematics, the <term>perimeter</term> means the length of that boundary. </p> 

  <example><statement>
    <sidebyside widths="60% 30%" margins="0% 10%" valigns="middle middle"><p>To find the perimeter of the region at right we add up the lengths of its sides:
      <me>5+3+5+4+3=20</me>
    The perimeter of the region is 20 inches.</p>
      <image source="perim1.png"></image></sidebyside></statement></example>

  <note><sidebyside widths="50% 35%"><p>Imagine that you are walking around the edge of the region. (If it is a very small region, imagine that you are an ant walking around the region.) The distance that you walk in one circuit around the region is its perimeter.</p> 
        <image source="ants.png"></image></sidebyside></note>

  <exercise><statement><p>One reason you might want to find a perimeter is to calculate the amount of fence you need to surround a region.  Find the perimeter of the community garden shown below.
      <image source="perim2.png" width="60%"></image></p></statement>

  <answer><p>The perimeter is 267 feet.</p></answer></exercise>

 <assemblage><title>Perimeter</title>
  <p> To find the perimeter of a straight-sided figure:<ol>
      <li><p>Measure the length of each side.</p></li>
      <li><p>Add up the lengths of the sides.</p></li></ol></p></assemblage>

