<subsection><title>Estimating Area</title>

<p>What if square units don't fit evenly inside a region?</p>

<example><statement><p>Find the area of the triangle. The grid represents inches.</p>
  <image source="areatri.png" width="30%"></image></statement>

<solution><p>This is actually an easy example, because the diagonal side of the triangle cuts each unit square in half. So we can pair up the 6 half-squares to make 3 whole squares. Adding those squares to the 15 whole squares, we find that the area is
  <me>15 + 3 = 18 ~\text{square inches}</me></p></solution></example>

<note><sidebyside widths="60% 30%"><p>Here is another way to find the area of the triangle in the last Example. Note that the triangle is actually half of a rectangle, as shown at right. The rectangle has 6 rows of 6 squares each, so its area is
  <me>6 \times 6 = 36 ~\text{square inches}</me>
The area of the triangle is half of that, or 18 square inches.</p>
    <image source="areatri.png"></image></sidebyside></note>

<p>The method described in the Note above is useful in many situations. We can enclose the figure in a rectangle, and subtract the areas that are not inside the region.</p>

<example><statement><p>Find the area enclosed by the octagon shown below. The grid represents centimeters.</p>
  <image source="octarea.png" width = "30%"></image></statement>

<solution><p><sidebyside widths="60% 30%"><p>Imagine enclosing the octagon in a rectangle, as shown at right. You can check that the rectangle encloses 7 rows of squares, and each row is 7 squares long. Thus, the area of the rectangle is
  <me>7 \times 7 = 49 ~\text{square inches}</me>
Now we just need to subtract the areas of the four "corners" of the rectangle.</p>
    <image source="cornersoct.png"></image></sidebyside></p>

<p>By looking at the top left corner, perhaps you can see that each of the four corners is half of a square whose area is 4 square centimeters. So each corner has an area of 2 square centimeters, and all four corners have a total area of 8 square centimeters.</p>
<p>Finally, we subtract the area of the corners from the area of the rectangle, and what's left is the area inside the octagon:
  <me>49 - 8 = 41 ~\text{square inches}</me></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Find the area of the <term>parallelogram</term>. Enclose the figure in a rectangle, then subtract the areas that are not inside the parallelogram. The grid represents centimeters.</p>
  <image source="paralarea.png" width="40%"></image></statement>

<answer><p>22 sq cm</p></answer></exercise>

<p>We have investigated three different ways to calculate the area of a region.</p>

<assemblage><title>Some methods for calculating area:</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Count the unit squares enclosed in the region, including your estimate of the number of whole squares made up of partial 
  squares.</p></li>
<li><p>Use multiplication to calculate the number of unit squares inside a rectangle.</p></li>
<li><p>Enclose the region in an imaginary rectangle, calculate the area of the rectangle, and then subtract the areas of the parts outside the region.</p></li>
</ol></p></assemblage>

